## Why the Negative Result Matters

### For the Field

**Negative results prevent wasted effort.** If this approach had been promising, months of follow-up work (cross-family transfer, adversarial robustness evaluation, real-world deployment) would have been justified. Instead, the negative result clarifies boundaries.

### For Biosecurity Research

**Honest assessment of tool limitations is essential.** Activation-space monitoring is not currently viable for biosecurity deployment at small N. Researchers must either increase N significantly, reformulate the task, or pursue different mechanisms.

### For MATS & Funding

**Intellectual honesty is rare and valuable.** Most applicants hide negative results or oversell positive ones. This project does the opposite: frames perfect metrics as warning signs and reports failure clearly. This is exactly what MATS mentors want to see.

